Ask HN: Are there good certificates for Developers?
text:
I once was a working student of a cybersecurity company. they required for each new hire to complete the famous OSCP certificate within 3 months.

they did that in order to make sure that their new hire is up for the task and probably because they can sell their services better to their clients.

Now I run a WebDev agency of my own with partly frontend-devs, backend-devs, fullstack-devs and DevOps guys - There are known cloud-native-foundation certificates for DevOps guys as well as certificates for the major cloud providers (AWS, Azure, etc), but I didnt find any good ones for lets say react or nodejs devs.

Since I want my employees to have a good coding standard/knowledge I thought of having such certificates for them as well, but I am still unsure whether its a good idea or rather a waste of time.

are they well received in the western world (We are from germany)?

does my favorite community has some thoughts on that topic?

Ask HN: Has anyone had success with using or developing Power Apps for Teams?
text:
I recently developed an app for a client. It was a replacement for an ancient PHP app. Due to the lower user licensing costs, the request was to stick to a Canvas app in the Teams environment.

The project was successful, app works, client is happy.

I realize that the common response on this site full of actual devs has been not very keen on low/no code tools, but for this extremely(15 years) out of practice developer they are a god send. I am able to single-dev a simple app and deliver it to a client. Via the enforced Teams integration, the apps are automatically available on desktop and mobile.

I am curious if any HN'ers have had success in developing or using just Canvas apps inside Teams, in your org.
